name: MockHttpSession
comment:
A mock session, intended to be used with redstone/redstone_mocks.MockRequest.

Usage:

var session = new MockHttpSession("session_1", {"username": "user"});
var req = new MockRequest("/service", session: session);
app.dispatch(req).then((resp) {
  ...
});

onTimeout=.name: onTimeout=
onTimeout=.comment: Sets a callback that will be called when the session is timed out.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no key-value pair in the map.

isNew.name: isNew
isNew.comment: Is true if the session has not been sent to the client yet.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one key-value pair in the map.

keys.name: keys
keys.comment:
The keys of this.

The returned iterable has efficient length and contains operations, based on redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.length and redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.containsKey of the map.

The order of iteration is defined by the individual Map implementation, but must be consistent between changes to the map.

length.name: length
length.comment: The number of key-value pairs in the map.

values.name: values
values.comment:
The values of this.

The values are iterated in the order of their corresponding keys. This means that iterating redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.keys and redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.values in parrallel will provided matching pairs of keys and values.

The returned iterable has an efficient length method based on the redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.length of the map.

[].comment: Returns the value for the given redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.[].key or null if redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.[].key is not in the map. Because null values are supported, one should either use redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.containsKey to distinguish between an absent key and a null value, or use the redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.putIfAbsent method.

[]=.comment:
Associates the redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.[]=.key with the given redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.[]=.value.

If the key was already in the map, its associated value is changed. Otherwise the key-value pair is added to the map.

addAll.name: addAll
addAll.comment:
Adds all key-value pairs of redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.addAll.other to this map.

If a key of redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.addAll.other is already in this map, its value is overwritten.

The operation is equivalent to doing this[key] = value for each key and associated value in other. It iterates over redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.addAll.other, which must therefore not change during the iteration.

clear.name: clear
clear.comment:
Removes all pairs from the map.

After this, the map is empty.

containsKey.name: containsKey
containsKey.comment: Returns true if this map contains the given key.

containsValue.name: containsValue
containsValue.comment: Returns true if this map contains the given value.

destroy.name: destroy
destroy.comment: Destroys the session. This will terminate the session and any further connections with this id will be given a new id and session.

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment:
Applies redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.forEach.f to each {key, value} pair of the map.

Adding or removing keys from the map during iteration is not allowed.

putIfAbsent.name: putIfAbsent
putIfAbsent.comment:
If redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.putIfAbsent.key is not associated to a value, calls redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent and updates the map by mapping redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.putIfAbsent.key to the value returned by redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent. Returns the value in the map.

Map<String, int> scores = {'Bob': 36};
for (var key in ['Bob', 'Rohan', 'Sophena']) {
  scores.putIfAbsent(key, () => key.length);
}
scores['Bob'];      // 36
scores['Rohan'];    //  5
scores['Sophena'];  //  7

The code that redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.putIfAbsent.ifAbsent executes must not add or remove keys.

remove.name: remove
remove.comment: Removes the association for the given redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.remove.key. Returns the value for redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.remove.key in the map or null if redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.remove.key is not in the map. Note that values can be null and a returned null value does not always imply that the key is absent.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the redstone/redstone_mocks.MockHttpSession.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.
